<br>
<br>
<DIV class="poemtitle">Red Tartar Mare</DIV><br>
<TABLE><TR><TD>
<br /> 
Hooves break the mirrors of<br /> 
the steppe lakes,<br /> 
clouds scud at her feet,<br /> 
miles of sky<br /> 
below her neck.<br /> 
Red silk tassels swing.<br /> 
The woman on her back<br /> 
sings at the summer skylarks.<br /> 
Tien Shan rise like<br /> 
heaven's blue wall&#8212;<br /> 
celestial mountains.<br /> 
<br /> 
Moving among<br /> 
nomadic peoples,<br /> 
they give her tarasun&#8212;<br /> 
vodka made from the milk of<br /> 
their mares&#8212;<br /> 
dried goat meat,<br /> 
a bag of mushrooms,<br /> 
an embroidered jacket of<br /> 
saffron silk<br /> 
and soft boots for her feet.<br /> 
<br /> 
She is going far.<br /> 
by her fires at night<br /> 
the mushrooms guide her.<br /> 
<br /> 
And each day <br /> 
under the red sun<br /> 
she moves farther from me.<br /> 
<br /> 
Now, unless I am<br /> 
at heart a falcon<br /> 
and swift enough to<br /> 
trace the silk roads<br /> 
before winter,<br /> 
I am afraid she will be<br /> 
swallowed forever<br /> 
into the heart of this vast land.<br /> 
<br /> 
While standing on the<br /> 
inland shores of the seas of grass,<br /> 
I remember the laughing girl<br /> 
who long ago rode a red Tartar mare<br /> 
to my own back door<br /> 
<br /> 
&#8212;the beads she braided then<br /> 
into her dark hair<br /> 
sounded like<br /> 
<i>chayir, chayir</i>&#8212;<br /> 
<br /> 
how we would lie together in the meadow<br /> 
and eat the stolen apples<br /> 
she brought in a bag.<br /> 
<br /> 
I am left behind<br /> 
to follow only stories<br /> 
of her passing<br /> 
from those nomads<br /> 
<br /> 
how she swept<br /> 
among them like the wind<br /> 
that snaps the prayer flags<br /> 
and lifts pyre smoke<br /> 
even to the gates of the palace<br /> 
of the Jade Emperor<br /> 
<br /> 
how the beads braided into the mane<br /> 
of the red Tartar mare she rode<br /> 
sounded like <i>chayir, chayir</i>.<br /> 
 

<br><br>

<a class="byline" href="javascript:goauthor('nelson-nold')">by Cindy Nelson-Nold</a></td></tr></table><br><br>
<br>
